### DFT upgrade

#### Oracle.

- DFT is not really abinito, so finding an oracle is more difficult that for HF.
  Neverhteless the class PeriodicTableSaito (now miss named) has GetEnergyDFT and those numbers come
  from NIST https://math.nist.gov/DFTdata/atomdata/tables/ptable.html.
  They have an exchange and a separate correlation potential described here: https://math.nist.gov/DFTdata/atomdata/node3.html#SECTION00021000000000000000
  and in this paper: S. H. Vosko, L. Wilk, and M. Nusair, Can. J. Phys. 58, 1200 (1980); S. H. Vosko and L. Wilk, Phys. Rev. B 22, 3812 (1980).
- libxc has the Vosko correlation implelemented.  See src/Hamiltonian/Internal/Libxc_LDA_Exchange.C
- BUT I tried some of simple exchange functions in libxc and using them I can't get agreement in the energies.
- I think we need to:
1. Consider separate `Vxc`, `Vex`, and `Vcorr` terms in src/Hamiltonian/Internal/Terms.C.
2. In src/Hamiltonian/Internal/Hamiltonians.C make new versions of Ham_DFT_{U,P}->Ham_DFTcorr_{U,P} and use separate Vex and Vcorr terms.
3. Hand code Vosko the exchange term so we have full control.
4. If we can reproduce the NIST energies then we have an oracle.

#### Friendly interface
- For libxc, the client code is expected to look up a function id.  Can we pick a few of the available functionals
  that we are likely to want for developing and testing in our work in BasisSet/Lattice_3D, (Si in particular) and make emuns for them.
  If the functionals require parameters, handle that for the user.  In short make the user unaware that libxc is under the hood.

#### How to handle Atom (pure radial) efficiently

- Every IBS basis set supports rvec_t op()(const rvec3_t&) for getting a vector of values needed for fitting ρ(r) and Vxc(ρ(r))
- This is the right interface for molecules and solids.  It is a little clunky for atoms, where efficiency suggests op()(double r) is better.
- Right now for atoms we make a mesh with an angular component going along one axis (say x, I forget which one). and that ends up feeding an rvec3_t(r,0,0) into op()(const rvec3_t&).
- Also atom op()(const rvec3_t&) does not inlcude any angular dependence, it is fake, just radial.  
- BUT in the future I want to make a flashy GUI app for atoms that can display orbitals (iso surfaces) with pretty colours.  In order for that work I need to use real versions of the spherical harmonics (Ylm+i*Yl-m etc) in order to plot the orbitals.
- THis will break DFT unless we use expensive grids with more angular directions.  Good source of numerical bugs.
- Looking for options to fix this.
1. make a separate op()(double r) just atoms.  Violates SOLID
2. Internal flag to indicate spherical harmonics on or off.
3. orther??
- We can deffer this decision until I do the flashy GUI app.

The cleaner framing: you're conflating evaluation with integration.

op()(rvec3_t) is the universal evaluation interface and should stay semantically honest — full angular dependence with real Ylm. That's what the GUI needs, and it's not optional truth.
Atomic DFT integration should exploit spherical symmetry analytically (1-D radial quadrature × 4π), not fake a 3-D grid down one axis. Make that a polymorphic integrator/quadrature strategy selected by the basis set's symmetry (the atom already carries YFactory symmetry — let that choose the radial integrator). The molecule/solid path uses a 3-D grid integrator.
So: don't fake op(), and don't flag it — separate the integration concern. A fast op()(double r) can exist as the internal fast-path the radial integrator calls, not as a public alternative. Deferring to GUI time is fine, but lock the principle now ("op(rvec3_t) is always honest") so the deferral doesn't quietly accrete a flag.

